data.title: London, England is not only place in the world with that name, here are 11 more
data.meta_description: Our London is not the only London in the world, here are 11 more places on planet Earth that share their name with the English capital.
data.text:
Ah London. Our capital, and for many people around the world, a city of dreams.

It’s so well known that the globe has around 50 names for it according to the Londonist.

However, what you might not know is that it’s not the only one. Other places liked the name so much they adopted too.

Here are 11 others Londons you may not have known about.

London in Burgundy, France

It turns out our closest neighbour has its own version of the British capital.

London in Burgundy is a small village in France 50 miles south of Dijon and specialises in agriculture.

It shot into fame in 2012 when Paddy Power sponsored their egg and spoon race in am ambush marekting campaign. The move got the bookmaker into trouble with 2012 Olympic Games organisers as they proclaimed themselves as the ‘Official sponsor of the largest athletics event in London this year!’.

London, Ontario

Close in language. Close in city names.

Canada’s London can be found in Southwestern Ontario with a population of 366,151. It has a pretty active tourism industry with a whole host of musical and artistic exhibits, and is also home to the University of Western Ontario.

What’s more, it even has its own Thames River. What could be more London?

London Island, Chile

Going a bit more remote: just off the coast of Chile are many islands, and London Island is one of them.

It can be found west of Tierra del Fuego, known for petrol extraction and Antarctic logistics.

There’s not much information nor photos of the island, but we imagine it’s probably as beautiful as this.

London, Arkansas

The U.S sure does love to name places after our capital City. This is one of eight Londons you can find in America.

This particular London is home to around 1,044 according the most recent population data. 96.7 per cent of them are white.

Trevor Drown, a Republican member of the Akansas House of Representatives, is a notable person from the area.

New London, Minnesota

Another city, but it’s not just London – it’s new.

It is most known as the start line for the New London to New Brighton Antique Car Run. Only old cars from 1908 and earlier can be drive on the 120-mile route.

The race runs every year in mid-August.

London, California

This London has a very different demographic to the one in Arkansas.

According to data from 2010, 92.9 per cent of residents are Hispanic.

London, Ohio

No one really knows why people called this town London – some believe that many of the people there in the 1800s or earlier were from Britain. Others thinks it was named after the company that surveyed the land, the London Company.

There are plenty of fun things to do here, including a strawberry festival in June and the Madison County Fair in July.

Could a place be more unlike the London we know?

Not a city, a town or even a village, the unincorporated community of London was built up in the 1800s. It was named London after a post office was established in 1882.

London, West Virginia

Another unincorporated community. It’s as industrial as it looks, being the home of London Locks and Dam built in 1933.

London, Wisconsin

Another area that came to be named London as many of the earlier settlers were natives of the original city.

It is home to the Glacial Drumlin trail, a railway named after common glacial landforms in the area.

London, Kiribati, Christmas Island

Ah finally, you’re thinking. A non-U.S London.

In fact it’s on the other side of the world near Australia.

It’s a principal settlement in the north of Christmas Island, known for its natural sights.
